SIMPLE: maiden
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Maiden
<hw>Maid"en</hw> <pr>(m⟦amac⟧d"'n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>maiden</ets>, <ets>meiden</ets>, AS. <ets>maegden</ets>, dim. of
AS. <ets>maeg⟦edh⟧</ets>, fr. <ets>mago</ets> son, servant; akin to G.
<ets>magd</ets>, <ets>m⟦aum⟧dchen</ets>, maid, OHG. <ets>magad</ets>,
Icel. <ets>m⟦oum⟧gr</ets> son, Goth. <ets>magus</ets> boy, child,
<ets>magaps</ets> virgin, and perh. to Zend. <ets>magu</ets> youth. Cf.
<er>Maid</er> a virgin.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An unmarried woman; a
girl or woman who has not experienced sexual intercourse; a virgin; a
maid.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She employed the residue of her life to repairing of highways,
building of bridges, and endowing of <qex>maidens</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Carew.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>maiden</qex> of our century, yet most meek.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A female servant.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An instrument resembling the guillotine, formerly
used in Scotland for beheading criminals.</def>
<rj><au>Wharton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A machine for washing linen.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maiden</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Maiden
<hw>Maid"en</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a
maiden, or to maidens; suitable to, or characteristic of, a virgin;
<as>as, <ex>maiden</ex> innocence</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Amid the
<xex>maiden</xex> throng.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Have you no modesty, no <qex>maiden</qex> shame ?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Never having been married; not having had sexual
intercourse; virgin; -- said usually of the woman, but sometimes of the
man; <as>as, a <ex>maiden</ex> aunt</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A surprising old
<xex>maiden</xex> lady.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Fresh; innocent; unpolluted; pure; hitherto
unused.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Maiden</xex> flowers.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Full bravely hast thou fleshed⟦br⟧
Thy <qex>maiden</qex> sword.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Used of a fortress, signifying that it has never
been captured, or violated.</def> <rj><au> T. Warton.
Macaulay.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Maiden assize</b></col> <fld>(Eng. Law)</fld>, <cd>an
assize which there is no criminal prosecution; an assize which is
unpolluted with blood. It was usual, at such an assize, for the sheriff
to present the judge with a pair of white gloves.</cd> <au>Smart.</au>
-- <col><b>Maiden name</b></col>, <cd>the surname of a woman before her
marriage.</cd> -- <col><b>Maiden pink</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld>
<cd>See under <er>Pink</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Maiden plum</b></col>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a West Indian tree (<spn>Comocladia
integrifolia</spn>) with purplish drupes. The sap of the tree is
glutinous, and gives a persistent black stain.</cd> -- <col><b>Maiden
speech</b></col>, <cd>the first speech made by a person, esp. by a new
member in a public body.</cd> -- <col><b>Maiden tower</b></col>, <cd>the
tower most capable of resisting an enemy.</cd> -- <col><b>maiden
voyage</b></col> <cd>the first regular service voyage of a
ship.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maiden</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Maiden
<hw>Maid"en</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To act coyly like a maiden; --
with <xex>it</xex> as an indefinite object.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For had I <qex>maiden'd</qex> it, as many use.⟦br⟧
Loath for to grant, but loather to refuse.</q> <rj><qau>Bp.
Hall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Maiden grass</b></col>, <cd>the smaller quaking
grass.</cd> -- <col><b>Maiden tree</b></col>. <cd>See
<er>Ginkgo</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maiden aunt</ent>⟦br⟧
